  <fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J\subseteq  A]]></fr:tex> be a directed subset such that every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  J]]></fr:tex> is positive; we must show that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigsqcup {J}]]></fr:tex> is positive. Fixing a subdirected subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\subseteq  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigsqcup {J}\sqsubseteq  \bigsqcup  I]]></fr:tex>, we must check that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is inhabited. The inequality <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigsqcup {J}\sqsubseteq  \bigsqcup  I]]></fr:tex> holds if and only if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\sqsubseteq  \bigsqcup {I}]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  u]]></fr:tex>; as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> is directed, we therefore have some positive <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\sqsubseteq  \bigsqcup {I}]]></fr:tex> from which it follows that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is inhabited.</fr:p>
